x4freetext: Experimental
procedure.
Natural silicon target, thickness 250 mug/cm**2,
evaporated onto a backing consisting of a 40 mug/cm**2
gold layer on a kapton film.
.Analysis of the experimental data was performed
by coherently adding specific resonances to an
underlying optical model which describes the background
portion of the direct elastic scattering amplitude.
A-spectra was measured.
Regge-pole parameters obtained from the best fits to
the experimental angular distributions in the
energy region associated with the fluctuation centred
at E(CM)=6.0 MeV.
100-micron silicon detectors. This detector
thickness was chosen in order to eliminate the need for
particle indentification, since protons with energies
above 3.5-MeV penetrated the detector. Forward angle
elastic scattering from a thin gold target, measured on
both sides of the beam, was used to determine the
angular offset of the angle determinations.
.The uncertainty is shown by authors on figure.
Data-point reader uncertainty.
The systematic error in the measured cross section
values, which is mainly due to uncertainties in the
silicon and gold target thicknesses, is estimated to be
less than 10%.

x4freetext: The 6-MV Van de Graaff accelerator.
-By authors. Rutherford scattering from the thin gold
layer sandwiched between the silicon target material
and the kapton backing, was used to monitor the total
incident flux. Data were collected to a statistical
accuracy of better than 5%.
- By compiler. The data were published as function of
the sum of projectile and target energies in C.-M.
System. The energies were recalculated to alpha
particle beam energy in laboratory frame system.
Original data are saved in MISC-COL.
.By CAJAD.
